 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "#_01_—_B",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "# 01 — Basic Fall Simulation\n\nWelcome to **ropesim**! This notebook walks through the fundamentals:\ncreating a rope, setting up a fall, running the simulation, and reading the results.\n\nNo climbing experience required — every physics term is explained inline."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_1._Im",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 1. Import ropesim\n\nMake sure you've run `pip install ropesim` (or `maturin develop` from the repo)."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "import_r",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "import ropesim\nprint(f'ropesim version: {ropesim.__version__}')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_2._En",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 2. Enable rich notebook display\n\nImporting `ropesim.notebook` patches all ropesim classes with `_repr_html_()` so they render as styled cards."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "import_r",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "import ropesim.notebook  # enables HTML display for Rope, FallResult, etc."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_3._Br",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 3. Browse the rope database\n\nThe built-in database contains dozens of ropes with full EN 892 spec data."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "from_rop",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "from ropesim import Rope, RopeDatabase\n\ndb = RopeDatabase()\nprint(f'Database contains {len(db)} ropes')\nprint('\\nFirst 5 ropes:')\nfor name in list(db.names())[:5]:\n    print(f'  {name}')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_4._Cr",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 4. Create a Rope object\n\nWe'll use a popular single dry rope. Displaying it in the notebook shows a formatted spec card."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "rope_=_R",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "rope = Rope.from_db('Beal Opera 8.5 Dry')\nrope  # renders as HTML card thanks to ropesim.notebook"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_5._Se",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 5. Set up fall conditions\n\nKey parameters:\n- **fall_distance_m**: how far the climber falls (metres)\n- **rope_out_m**: total rope between belay and climber (metres)\n- **fall_factor** = fall_distance / rope_out — the key UIAA metric (0–2)\n\nHere we simulate a fall factor 1.0 scenario: 10 m fall on 10 m of rope."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "from_rop",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "from ropesim import FallConditions, BelayDevice\n\nconditions = FallConditions(\n    climber_mass_kg  = 80.0,\n    fall_distance_m  = 10.0,\n    rope_out_m       = 10.0,\n    belay_device     = BelayDevice.GRIGRI,\n    rope             = rope.spec,\n)\nprint(f'Fall factor: {conditions.fall_distance_m / conditions.rope_out_m:.2f}')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_6._Ru",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 6. Run the simulation"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "from_rop",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "from ropesim import Fall\n\nresult = Fall(conditions).simulate()\nresult  # rich HTML card with force curve"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_7._Ac",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 7. Access result fields directly\n\nAll fields are plain Python attributes — easy to use in scripts."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "print(f'",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "print(f'Peak force:      {result.peak_force_kn:.2f} kN ({result.peak_force_lbf:.0f} lbf)')\nprint(f'Peak decel:      {result.peak_deceleration_g:.1f} g')\nprint(f'Fall factor:     {result.fall_factor:.3f}')\nprint(f'Rope elongation: {result.elongation_m*100:.1f} cm')\nif result.warnings:\n    print('\\nWarnings:')\n    for w in result.warnings:\n        print(f'  - {w}')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_8._Co",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 8. Compare belay devices\n\nThe choice of belay device significantly affects peak force on the anchor."
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "import_m",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt\n\ndevices = [\n    BelayDevice.TUBE,\n    BelayDevice.ATC,\n    BelayDevice.REVERSO,\n    BelayDevice.REVERSO_GUIDE,\n    BelayDevice.GRIGRI,\n    BelayDevice.MEGAJUL,\n    BelayDevice.I_DEVICE,\n]\nforces = []\nfor d in devices:\n    conds = FallConditions(climber_mass_kg=80.0, fall_distance_m=10.0,\n                           rope_out_m=10.0, belay_device=d, rope=rope.spec)\n    r = Fall(conds).simulate()\n    forces.append(r.peak_force_kn)\n\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 3.5))\ncolours = ['#5b9bd5' if not d.value.endswith(('guide','jul','device','up','sum'))\n           else '#e67e22' for d in devices]\nbars = ax.barh([d.value for d in devices], forces, color=colours)\nax.set_xlabel('Peak anchor force (kN)')\nax.set_title('Belay device comparison — FF 1.0, 80 kg climber')\nax.axvline(9.0, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.8, label='EN 892 limit')\nax.legend(fontsize=8)\nfor bar, val in zip(bars, forces):\n    ax.text(val + 0.05, bar.get_y() + bar.get_height()/2,\n            f'{val:.2f} kN', va='center', fontsize=8)\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()\nprint('Orange bars = guide-mode / self-locking devices')"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_9._Pl",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 9. Plot the force-time curve"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": null,
   "id": "import_n",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": "import numpy as np\n\ncurve = np.array(result.force_curve)\nt_ms  = np.arange(len(curve))  # each step is 1 ms by default\n\nfig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(8, 3))\nax.plot(t_ms, curve, color='#2270c4')\nax.fill_between(t_ms, curve, alpha=0.15, color='#2270c4')\nax.axhline(result.peak_force_kn, color='red', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.8,\n           label=f'Peak: {result.peak_force_kn:.2f} kN')\nax.set_xlabel('Time (ms)')\nax.set_ylabel('Rope force (kN)')\nax.set_title('Force vs time — Grigri belay, FF 1.0')\nax.legend()\nplt.tight_layout()\nplt.show()"
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "##_10._K",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": "## 10. Key takeaways\n\n- **Fall factor** (not absolute fall height) determines peak force for lead falls.\n- Guide-mode devices (orange bars) produce **significantly lower** anchor forces because friction increases with load — the device locks the rope progressively.\n- The force-time curve peaks sharply the